aetfst 01 Portland on O. R. N. Railway,\nllvii etuiprd Sanatorium and Surgery in North writ,\nBOILING HOT SPRINGS\nHighly Minetalized\nAsk agi-nts (or ipucial rate round trip ticket..\nWrite for llluatratrd booklet to\nDR. W. T. PHY\nMedical Supr. and Mgr. HOT LAKE, ORKCON\nPOLK'S GAZETTEER i\nA I!u?Inps9 THrprtory of oaeli City.\nTown and Villain- ln On-Kn mid\nWashington, (.'iWnff a idsirlptlve\nSketrli ot pni'li lilnco, Locution,\nr-hiiiin(f Facilities unit a Chissl-\ntli,l Diroctory of each Business\nand Profession.\nn. i.. roi.K co inc.\nScuttlf. Vii!i.\nC. F. COOK, President and Mannger F. 1L COOK, Treasurer\nF. J. NEWMAN, Secretary\nRogue River Valley Nursery Co.\nIncorporated\nmepfori), op.fgon\nBULKS OF ALL KINDS SEEDS OF ALL KINDS\nGrowers of Reliable Nnrseiy Slock, Fruit and Ornamental Trees,\nShrubs, Roses, Vines, Palms, Small Fruits, Etc.\nWrite for Prices\nPhone l'JOl\nOffice West Main Street\nNEW YORK. Nov. 2. Wall street\nIs reflecting the fight for Increased\nfreight rates now being waged by the\nprincipal railroads of the country.\nThat Is the view of prominent New\nYork business men, although they\nassert that \"business conditions are\nbeing manipulated to affect manu\nfatruring sentiment' In' favor of the\nIncreased tariffs.\" That the warn\nings that already have been noted on\nthe delicate business barometer of\nthe ticker tape are only tentative as\nyet, but that they may produce a\ntempest Is the opinion of close ob\nservers of the game here. The rail\nroads are anxious to secure the rate\nIncreases which would amount, it Is\nestimated, to $73,000,000 yearly.\nThe money would come first from\nthe manufacturers, though ultimate\nly the consumer would doubtless be\ncalled upon to pay. The result that\ntwo great business forces the man\nufacturers and the railroads are\nfighting against each other and their\nallied forces In the street are feel\ning the effect of the fight. That Is\nthe way the followers of the doings\nof the slreet view the situation.\nWall street Itself Is Inclined to\naccept as true the statement of\nJames J. Hill, the veteran railroader,\n\"that business conditions are not sat\nisfactory.\" The News Rurcau, a\nWall street organ, declares that the\nreason for tho unrest ln financial\ncircles Is \"because railroads and cor\nporations are determined to proceed\ncautiously until the rate question\nand other similar matters have been\nsettled.\"\nUnless rates are increased, orders\nfor new equipment will be cancelled\nby the railroads and the old Inten\ntion of abandoning Improvements\nand extensions will again be voiced,\naccording to tho Railway Business\nassociation.\nSuch a procedure would mean the\nshutting down of car shops and of\nrepair shops of the railroads, lessen\nled demand for supplies and a gen\nleral business depression. In the\njfaee of those conditions stockbrokers\nsay, it Is not surprising that there\nshould be a tendency toward falling\nprices. A slump in United States\nSteel. Union Pacific and Rending\njwas no surprise to the brokers.\nI Some Wall street lenders nssert that\njnttompts on the part of the big busi\nness Interests to make Hill's Bum\nmlii 5 up of the case appear true\nenough to Impress\nMISSOURI FLAT\nM. B. Butler, of Portland, Is visit\ning with his uncle, J. X. Butler, and\nfamily.\nW. W. Wooldrldge and the Misses\nPearl Davidson, Anna Stannard and\nFleda Wooldrldge attended the\nThanksgiving dance at Ruch and re\nport having a fine time.\nWe are having a steady downpour\nof rain and Applegate river bids fair\nto be higher than any time last year.\nJohn Meek and Mabel Martin\nwere married at Trovolt Saturday,\nNovember 26. Miss Martin is a\ndaughter of Mr. and Mrs. Jas. Mar\ntin, who now live at Klamath Falls j\nbut were former residents of the\nFlat. Mr. Meek has grown up fn\nour midst and both young people are\nhighly respected. Quite a crowd\nwent over from the literary Satur\nday night and tendered them our\n\"greetings\" in charivari form. Their\nmany friends join ln wishing them a\nhappy and prosperous Journey on\nthrough life.\nOne of Frank Ralley's children Is\nvery sick at ths writing.\nThere Is a very light attendance at\nschool this week on account of the\nvery high water.\nThe Famous Mmf\nIs the Lamp ot tieal veamy\nbecause it gives the best light of all\nlamps. The Rayo gives a white, soft,\nmellow, diffused light-easy on the\neye because it cannot flicker. You\ncan use your eyes as long as you wish\nunder the Rayo light without strain.\nThe Rayo Lamp is low-priced, and\neven though you pay $5, $10 or $20 for\nother lamps, you may get more expensive\ndecorations but you cannot get a better\nlight than the low-priced Rayo gives. A\nstrong, durable shade-holder holds the\nshade on firm and true. This season s\nnew burner adds strength and appearance.\nCine a Ravo User, Always One.\nr..r b,.-,,,.- ttmat at tours, vritt for itscriptii\nj&J Standard OU Company\n1 1 n f it n r n I el 1\n3.\n1 WIWJ\" \"V\"'\"\nai\nDANDRl 1 T EASILY (\"I'REO\nIn fact, C. H. Deimiray, the drug-\nNext Saturday night there Is to be gist, has a certain hair restorer call-\ni i t... Cniv. iv men costs only\na mock trial at literary. Some one;-; fl bo(Ut, that ls RHar.\nwill be arrested for oh. well, It jntotvi to cure dandruff In two weeks\nmav be von, but come out any way 'or money back,\nand enjoy a good time. Parisian Sage Is the overy of\nJan eminent student, scientist nndspe\nMiss Rhea Cook is on the sick list j ciallst. and is made in this country\nthis week. U. R. STUNG. only by the Clroux Mfg Co., Buffalo.\nX. Y.\nParisian Sage is a most pleasant,\nMURPHY\nTi. W. Carson and James Lindsny\nleu ior ronianu csunuaj uu tt i-.-w r v,i ,h\n10 StOI) 1UIIIUK nun in io.....n v,\ndays' vacation. I scalp.\nMr and Mrs. Ceo. Herrlott. of it will make hair grow, and women\nApplegate were visiting at the home j;h desire soft bpnutlful x\n4 riant nair can have It ln two weens\nof Mr. and Mrs. J. Darnellle last ,)y us)nR th,3 fam0USi qtri